WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.600
So now let's dive into the best practices for developing shiny apps. So actually you

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:22.280
can build apps that last. And in my talk, I'm going to cover T areas, which is organizing

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:29.360
a shiny app code, organizing your development environment, and organizing your testing.

00:00:29.360 --> 00:00:34.880
Since we have limited amount of time, this will be a high-level overview talk, and I'm

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:40.320
going to introduce concepts and tools you should be using and tell you why. So if you

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:48.680
are not familiar with them, you can explore them in more details after the talk.

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:57.040
So how should you organize the code inside your shiny app? First answer is use shiny

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:03.680
modules. So shiny modules let you decompose your application. So you can follow a don't

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:14.400
repeat yourself coding principle. They offer encapsulation, modularity, reusability, and

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:21.639
allow you to test the whole components. They allow you to organize your app in the server

00:01:21.639 --> 00:01:30.839
and the UI part, which in essence mean that you can define your own pair of server and

00:01:30.839 --> 00:01:41.040
UI logic and use it inside your app or embed it in the other module.

00:01:41.040 --> 00:01:50.120
So secondly, you can also organize your code using R6 classes. And an R6 class is a modern

00:01:50.120 --> 00:01:57.680
and fast and simple implementation of object-oriented programming in R.

00:01:57.680 --> 00:02:05.400
You can look at it as a more organized shiny module. And R6 classes introduces a clear

00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:12.080
system of getting the current state of the piece of functionality, the operations that can be

00:02:12.080 --> 00:02:18.759
performed with it, the auxiliary functions, and the initial state of the object that can depend on

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:23.520
the particular user rights, which might be actually super useful.

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:30.720
So how do you organize your code using R6 classes? So you can keep each class in a separate

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:38.639
script with a name similar to the class name. You can store the script in a folder separated

00:02:38.639 --> 00:02:47.679
from the other code. You can import the code using a package or as in here in the example,

00:02:47.679 --> 00:02:56.639
using a use function from the modules package. And then you can initialize the class with a new

00:02:56.639 --> 00:03:04.559
method, which is ultimately available for all the classes and attach it to some object.

00:03:04.559 --> 00:03:17.240
And the third option is to use modules from the honey. And I would like to avoid some

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:24.199
confusion with shiny modules. So the modules I'm going to talk right now is something completely

00:03:24.199 --> 00:03:33.119
different from shiny modules. So the modules are the organizational unit for the source code,

00:03:33.119 --> 00:03:41.360
and they can contain shiny modules or R6 classes or just functions you define.

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:47.759
And the cool thing about them is that they enforce rigor when defining the dependencies.

00:03:47.759 --> 00:03:58.000
It means that you have to explicitly declare which functions or packages your code is using and you have to import them.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:07.320
And you also have a full control of the things that are available outside the module because you have to export them

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:11.800
using the export function as shown here in the example.

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:19.839
And additionally, they have a local search path and they can be used as a subunit within the package or in scripts.

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:24.920
So to put it all together, shiny modules are six classes and modules.

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:30.279
So shiny modules, they let you reuse UI and the server part of the components.

00:04:30.279 --> 00:04:36.559
R6 classes, they let you build objects that have a single responsibility and implement given logic.

00:04:36.559 --> 00:04:48.399
And behind modules, they encapsulate dependencies and let you organize files that could be shiny modules and R6 classes as a separate unit.

00:04:48.399 --> 00:05:03.160
So, OK, we covered how we organize the code. So now let's talk about the development environment and how you can organize it.

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:15.799
So continuous integration to ensure quality and automate checks, you can run lint and test automatically for every push change.

00:05:15.799 --> 00:05:20.320
And especially for tests, you probably will forget to run them every time.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:24.600
So just automate it so you don't think you don't have to think about it.

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:36.679
And additionally, you can automatically add a pull request template that can contain a checklist for a pull request creator and the reviewer to every pull request.

00:05:36.679 --> 00:05:49.160
You can push, you can block pushing directly to master and block pull requests, merging pull requests if the test fails.

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:57.679
So here are some popular continuous integration options, Bitbucket, CircleCI, Travis Jenkins and GitHub Actions.

00:05:57.679 --> 00:06:04.640
So I'm sure you will find something that will fit your technology stack.

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:13.760
And remember, you don't have to start from scratch every time and you can use a project template for it.

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:27.399
So at Epsilon, we have an internal project pattern with a Shiny boilerplate template and we use it to initialize the repository structure if we start a new project.

00:06:27.399 --> 00:06:33.920
And it contains a simple Shiny app with modules and Shiny modules set up.

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:46.799
It also contains a sample unit test and the CI with Lint and automatic unit tests set up.

00:06:46.799 --> 00:06:54.640
OK, so how actually your development environment should look like?

00:06:54.640 --> 00:07:00.079
So let's start from the other way.

00:07:00.079 --> 00:07:03.440
So what happens if you don't take care of it?

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:11.559
So development environment is a crucial part of working in R and it's not only Shiny specific.

00:07:11.559 --> 00:07:21.640
So otherwise, if you don't take care of it, you can end up with the same code giving different results on different machines.

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:28.760
Other projects can be affected as in the global environment, shared package can change and crash unrelated projects.

00:07:28.799 --> 00:07:36.480
You can imagine the deployment is long and difficult as establishing infrastructure is challenging if it's not being tracked.

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:43.959
And last but not least, team will waste time setting up a new environment rather than jumping straight to work.

00:07:43.959 --> 00:07:53.000
So this might not be a problem when you're starting a project, but imagine that you have to urgently add a new team member in the middle of one.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:59.880
So to solve all those problems, we recommend a following setup.

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:08.959
So you can do a development in RStudio running inside the Docker container, which is fixed and dedicated per project.

00:08:08.959 --> 00:08:16.440
And you can leverage Docker and RENV package to control underlying system, system dependencies and R packages.

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:20.920
And Docker and RENV together make team collaboration easy.

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:34.799
So all the changes to Docker file and RENV log file that records the packages used in the project are committed to the Docker repository and to the code repository.

00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:39.840
For example, GitHub that your team is using.

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:46.479
On the other hand, the previous solution still requires some level of DevOps skills.

00:08:46.479 --> 00:09:06.080
And what we observe with our clients, especially the enterprise one, they choose to work with RStudio Server Pro that allows their data science team to purely focus on delivering value using their core competencies in a highly secure and flexible environment.

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:19.880
Obviously, here you still want to use RENV to control the R dependencies and keep them separate for every project so different team members can easily collaborate.

00:09:19.880 --> 00:09:32.080
So the last bit I'm going to talk is testing and my message.

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:36.559
And my message here is just do it.

00:09:36.559 --> 00:09:41.599
The only question is what test and in what proportion you should be writing.

00:09:41.599 --> 00:09:46.159
And we will use a testing pyramid to answer that.

00:09:46.159 --> 00:09:50.000
So you should aim to have the most unique tests and data validation.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:10:04.000
The next test up components, aka test your Shiny modules, test the whole scenarios with end to end testing, perform load tests and finally test usability with user interest views.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:14.039
And now let's quickly talk about the tools you have available.

00:10:14.039 --> 00:10:18.239
So for unit tests, I'm sure you all know the test package.

00:10:18.239 --> 00:10:20.039
So just use it.

00:10:20.039 --> 00:10:36.280
But please set up your architecture early and don't tell yourself an excuse that you will do it later because that will probably won't happen because your Shiny application would be awesome and your clients or your business partners would like to move on to something else.

00:10:36.280 --> 00:10:39.640
So start each project with test architecture.

00:10:39.640 --> 00:10:44.919
You already know that you can have a project template to set up at the beginning.

00:10:44.919 --> 00:10:53.960
You also know that you can use a continuous integration to triggers the test automatically so you don't have to do it manually.

00:10:53.960 --> 00:11:02.000
And please write at least some tests for each piece of code and it would be easier to expand them later.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.440
And obviously, keep your standards high.

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:13.760
So do not accept requests that don't include tests or actually break them.

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:19.479
So now it's part for a data validation.

00:11:19.479 --> 00:11:22.799
And this is the this is the logic.

00:11:22.799 --> 00:11:29.960
This is the functionality that you should be doing on the same level as the unit tests.

00:11:29.960 --> 00:11:36.119
So as we all know from our experience, data can be very messy.

00:11:36.119 --> 00:11:42.880
And actually Kaggle users reported that this is their biggest pain, the dirty data.

00:11:42.919 --> 00:11:57.559
So I want to introduce you to a data validator package, which is a tool for creating reports based on our open site assert our results.

00:11:57.559 --> 00:12:08.239
And it allows you to create user friendly reports that can be generated automatically, for example, with RStudio Connect.

00:12:08.239 --> 00:12:12.440
So how can you use data validator package introduction?

00:12:12.440 --> 00:12:15.799
Here's the example workflow.

00:12:15.799 --> 00:12:29.640
So you can run RStudio Connect scheduler and the scheduler can source the data from a database and validate the results based on the validation results.

00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:35.479
A new data validator report is created and we have two scenarios here.

00:12:35.479 --> 00:12:37.599
So the validation fails.

00:12:37.599 --> 00:12:49.719
In that case, a report can be sent to responsible stakeholders so a responsible person can actually take action and fix things.

00:12:49.719 --> 00:12:53.239
And obviously, on the other hand, we also have positive scenarios.

00:12:53.239 --> 00:13:02.640
So everything is great. So the Shiny app can be refreshed with the new data.

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:07.960
And the next step that I'm going to cover is end-to-end testing.

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:15.479
So the phase when you are actually testing the full components in your app.

00:13:15.479 --> 00:13:22.840
And luckily, we have the Shiny test package from RStudio and that it's easy to use for developers.

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:28.719
You can record the scenarios and this provides a quick and simple way to test your Shiny apps.

00:13:28.719 --> 00:13:35.000
On the other hand, for more complex apps, we recommend using Cypress.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:45.520
But please be aware that it requires knowledge of JavaScript, but it's really, really powerful.

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:53.080
And we reached the point that your application actually is ready to go live.

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:58.200
So you want to make sure that it's able to handle the traffic.

00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:07.400
So here you can use Shiny load test package that enables you to load test your deployed apps.

00:14:07.400 --> 00:14:11.200
You can estimate how many users your app can support.

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:22.000
You can identify bottlenecks and you can use the test output to guide you through the changes if the optimization is actually necessary.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:26.080
OK, and the last bit that you really have to think about.

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:32.520
So you also want to make sure that what you're actually building is useful for your users.

00:14:32.520 --> 00:14:37.320
So please talk to them.

00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:44.039
And you don't need to have a big budget to do that because you can always use the hallway tests.

00:14:44.039 --> 00:14:51.559
And the idea here is that you can show the application to your colleagues or to end users.

00:14:51.559 --> 00:14:58.239
And let them click through it and they can describe what they are doing and what they understand is happening.

00:14:58.239 --> 00:15:08.119
And research showed that if you do it to five people, you will learn around 85 percent of the usability problems.

00:15:08.119 --> 00:15:17.200
And obviously, if you don't do it at all, you will learn zero problems.

00:15:17.239 --> 00:15:26.400
So the things I want you to take home, organize your code with Shiny modules, R6 classes or modules, depending on app complexity.

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:38.520
Use CI to run lint and tests. Use Renv to control R dependencies and automate code testing and data validations.

00:15:38.520 --> 00:15:39.479
Thank you very much.

